NNAAMMEE
       runargs - run a program with arguments read from an argument file

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       rruunnaarrggss [[--hhVV]] [[--ii]] _a_r_g_f_i_l_e _p_r_o_g_r_a_m [[ _a_r_g_s _._._.  ]]

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       rruunnaarrggss runs _p_r_o_g_r_a_m with arguments read from _a_r_g_f_i_l_e.

       An  _a_r_g_f_i_l_e  is  a  plain text file with zero or more lines.  Each line
       read is setup as an individual argument to _p_r_o_g_r_a_m in the same order as
       it  is read.  Any leading and/or trailing whitespace is trimmed.  Empty
       lines and lines beginning with the `#' character are ignored.

       If _a_r_g_f_i_l_e is given as a `--' character, arguments will  be  taken  from
       stdin.

       Normally any arguments specified in _a_r_g_s are setup to precede the argu-
       ments taken from _a_r_g_f_i_l_e.  The --ii option may be  used  to  invert  this
       order.

       If  _p_r_o_g_r_a_m does not contain a ``/'' slash character, rruunnaarrggss will per-
       form a shell-like search for the executable using the PPAATTHH variable  in
       the current environment.

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --hh     Help.  Print a brief usage message to stderr and exit.

       --ii     Insert.   Normally  rruunnaarrggss  sets  up _p_r_o_g_r_a_m with any arguments
              given in _a_r_g_s before those given in _a_r_g_f_i_l_e.  The --ii option  may
              be  used  to  invert  this order, and insert the arguments taken
              from _a_r_g_f_i_l_e before any specified in _a_r_g_s.

       --VV     Version.  Print the version number to stderr and exit.

EEXXIITT SSTTAATTUUSS
       rruunnaarrggss exits with one of the following values:

       0      _p_r_o_g_r_a_m was invoked and completed successfully.  In  this  case,
              the exit code is returned by the _p_r_o_g_r_a_m, rather than by rruunnaarrggss
              itself.

       100    rruunnaarrggss failed because of a usage error, such as an invalid com-
              mand-line  option  or  argument.  In this case, rruunnaarrggss prints a
              brief error message and usage help to stderr on exit.

       111    rruunnaarrggss failed due to some system or resource  error.   In  this
              case,  rruunnaarrggss  prints  a  brief diagnostic message to stderr on
              exit.

       1-127  _p_r_o_g_r_a_m was invoked and failed with its own non-zero  exit  sta-
              tus.

CCAAVVEEAATTSS
       In  most  cases,  the  arguments specified in _a_r_g_f_i_l_e will not normally
       want to follow the shell-protecting quoting conventions as might other-
       wise be used when running _p_r_o_g_r_a_m in a shell environment.

